00:00:37.420 --> 00:00:39.130
RETO MEIER: We thought the best
way to get back into the

00:00:39.130 --> 00:00:41.440
swing of things was to remind
everyone what the App Clinic

00:00:41.440 --> 00:00:42.200
is all about.

00:00:42.200 --> 00:00:44.240
IAN NI-LEWIS: And what better
way to do that than by showing

00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:46.270
off some of our graduates.

00:00:46.270 --> 00:00:48.150
And officially launching--

00:00:48.150 --> 00:00:50.115
RETO MEIER: Pure Android.

00:00:50.115 --> 00:00:52.390
IAN NI-LEWIS: Pure Android is a
Google Play collection that

00:00:52.390 --> 00:00:55.290
we, along with Roman, Nick, and
Adam from Android Design

00:00:55.290 --> 00:00:58.500
in Action will be curating.

00:00:58.500 --> 00:01:02.170
You can find it at bitly dot--
er, bit.ly is that--?

00:01:02.170 --> 00:01:03.150
Do we just say bitly?

00:01:03.150 --> 00:01:03.700
RETO MEIER: Yeah, I'll
just go with bitly.

00:01:03.700 --> 00:01:03.890
I think we just say bitly.

00:01:03.890 --> 00:01:05.450
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah.
bit.ly/PureAndroid.

00:01:05.450 --> 00:01:06.100
RETO MEIER: Yeah.

00:01:06.100 --> 00:01:08.520
It's a way for us to shine some
light on the Android apps

00:01:08.520 --> 00:01:10.260
that we've examined
during be App

00:01:10.260 --> 00:01:14.700
Clinic, often quite candidly.

00:01:14.700 --> 00:01:16.090
But they've really built
something beautiful and

00:01:16.090 --> 00:01:18.570
intuitive, and taken some
feedback that we've given to

00:01:18.570 --> 00:01:20.300
create something which
we really like.

00:01:20.300 --> 00:01:20.860
IAN NI-LEWIS: Right.

00:01:20.860 --> 00:01:22.870
It's also a small way of saying
thank you all the

00:01:22.870 --> 00:01:26.070
developers who submit their
apps to our constructive

00:01:26.070 --> 00:01:28.580
criticism, and who then turn
around and make their apps

00:01:28.580 --> 00:01:29.530
even better.

00:01:29.530 --> 00:01:30.780
RETO MEIER: And so we're
going to be adding

00:01:30.780 --> 00:01:31.930
to this list slowly.

00:01:31.930 --> 00:01:33.010
So there's only a couple
of apps that

00:01:33.010 --> 00:01:33.960
we'll be adding today.

00:01:33.960 --> 00:01:36.260
And we're going to hope to try
and find a couple of really

00:01:36.260 --> 00:01:38.640
good examples, maybe every week,
maybe every other week.

00:01:38.640 --> 00:01:39.410
So it's a list that
we hope to grow.

00:01:39.410 --> 00:01:40.165
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh yeah,
I've got a list.

00:01:40.165 --> 00:01:43.140
RETO MEIER: There's lots of
great apps out there, but we

00:01:43.140 --> 00:01:45.720
want to make sure we give each
app the opportunity to really

00:01:45.720 --> 00:01:46.740
shine by itself first.

00:01:46.740 --> 00:01:48.460
So that's why we're going
to go slowly.

00:01:48.460 --> 00:01:51.670
And every time we do induct
someone in our hall of fame,

00:01:51.670 --> 00:01:53.970
we're going to do it live on the
App Clinic, so stay tuned

00:01:53.970 --> 00:01:56.350
for the end of the show when
we're going to give you a

00:01:56.350 --> 00:01:59.180
little more details on what it
takes for you to create an app

00:01:59.180 --> 00:02:01.090
worthy of the Pure
Android title.

00:02:01.090 --> 00:02:01.940
IAN NI-LEWIS: Exactly.

00:02:01.940 --> 00:02:05.080
So today we're inducting two
apps into Pure Android, both

00:02:05.080 --> 00:02:07.780
of which we looked at in the
very early days of Android

00:02:07.780 --> 00:02:09.075
Developers Live.

00:02:09.075 --> 00:02:12.730
RETO MEIER: And that's Pattrn
by Lucas Rocha and Tasks by

00:02:12.730 --> 00:02:14.070
Team Tasks.

00:02:14.070 --> 00:02:16.570
And it's not just because
they're both using Apps Clinic

00:02:16.570 --> 00:02:17.610
as their color palette.

00:02:17.610 --> 00:02:20.565
IAN NI-LEWIS: Although, that
does tend to make, you know--

00:02:20.565 --> 00:02:21.060
yeah.

00:02:21.060 --> 00:02:22.600
RETO MEIER: It's not
going against them,

00:02:22.600 --> 00:02:23.260
I'll say that much.

00:02:23.260 --> 00:02:24.220
IAN NI-LEWIS: No, no.

00:02:24.220 --> 00:02:27.000
Let's start by taking
a look at Pattrn.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:27.630
RETO MEIER: All right.

00:02:27.630 --> 00:02:30.250
So right off the bat, you can
see that they've done a great

00:02:30.250 --> 00:02:32.490
job on a Google Play
feature page.

00:02:32.490 --> 00:02:34.250
The branding is really
striking.

00:02:34.250 --> 00:02:36.840
And it's still entirely
consistent between their logo

00:02:36.840 --> 00:02:38.270
and their feature graphic.

00:02:38.270 --> 00:02:40.120
And you can see how this
banner is really

00:02:40.120 --> 00:02:41.140
going to stand out.

00:02:41.140 --> 00:02:43.900
No matter what size it is, if it
does get featured in Google

00:02:43.900 --> 00:02:45.440
Play, you're going to
notice this banner.

00:02:45.440 --> 00:02:45.825
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah.

00:02:45.825 --> 00:02:48.580
And you can tell it's not just
that they've made something

00:02:48.580 --> 00:02:49.070
big and bold.

00:02:49.070 --> 00:02:51.110
They've also taken a lot
of care with the pixels

00:02:51.110 --> 00:02:51.740
themselves.

00:02:51.740 --> 00:02:53.770
They do have a little bit of
drop shadow, but it's not

00:02:53.770 --> 00:02:55.930
obvious, just to
separate them--

00:02:55.930 --> 00:02:59.260
the pattern from
the background.

00:02:59.260 --> 00:02:59.995
They've done some design.

00:02:59.995 --> 00:03:00.810
RETO MEIER: Absolutely.

00:03:00.810 --> 00:03:02.400
And that's really important
for the sort of

00:03:02.400 --> 00:03:03.270
app that this is.

00:03:03.270 --> 00:03:06.170
Something which is visual, which
people who care about

00:03:06.170 --> 00:03:07.470
designing would be
interested in.

00:03:07.470 --> 00:03:10.550
It really pays to take
that extra step and

00:03:10.550 --> 00:03:11.620
make that extra effort.

00:03:11.620 --> 00:03:12.560
IAN NI-LEWIS: Exactly.

00:03:12.560 --> 00:03:14.440
It also gives you a grade
A idea of what the

00:03:14.440 --> 00:03:15.765
apps going to do.

00:03:15.765 --> 00:03:17.150
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:03:17.150 --> 00:03:18.760
So throughout the
app, the design

00:03:18.760 --> 00:03:20.020
language is really clean.

00:03:20.020 --> 00:03:20.850
It's really uncluttered.

00:03:20.850 --> 00:03:23.650
It's intuitive and it's entirely
consistent with the

00:03:23.650 --> 00:03:24.985
Android Design Guide.

00:03:24.985 --> 00:03:27.153
And you can see that as you move
through the app you're

00:03:27.153 --> 00:03:29.530
never left wondering where you
are, what you should be doing.

00:03:29.530 --> 00:03:31.570
The navigation is obvious.

00:03:31.570 --> 00:03:32.880
The screen design
is really clear.

00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:34.980
There's not extra stuff
going on there.

00:03:34.980 --> 00:03:37.380
They've tried to keep it as
visual as possible and as

00:03:37.380 --> 00:03:39.930
non-intrusive as they can.

00:03:39.930 --> 00:03:42.140
And if you look at their tablet
layouts-- which is sort

00:03:42.140 --> 00:03:43.920
of key as well to being
pure Android.

00:03:43.920 --> 00:03:46.000
You can see that they've
implemented a fantastic

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:48.720
responsive design that
works well both in

00:03:48.720 --> 00:03:50.110
portrait and in landscape.

00:03:50.110 --> 00:03:52.710
And that's really important and
really exciting for me to

00:03:52.710 --> 00:03:54.640
see a great tablet experience
that works in both

00:03:54.640 --> 00:03:56.120
orientations.

00:03:56.120 --> 00:03:59.900
So we spoke to the developer
of Pattrn, Lucas, earlier.

00:03:59.900 --> 00:04:01.710
And we asked him to tell us a
little bit more about his

00:04:01.710 --> 00:04:05.606
experience building a
Pure Android app.

00:04:05.606 --> 00:04:07.060
LUCAS ROCHA: Hello.

00:04:07.060 --> 00:04:08.800
I'm Lucas Rocha.

00:04:08.800 --> 00:04:10.846
I'm the creator of Pattrn.

00:04:10.846 --> 00:04:14.510
It's a unique app, like a
wallpaper app, for Android

00:04:14.510 --> 00:04:15.890
phones and tablets.

00:04:15.890 --> 00:04:21.010
What's unique about it is that
instead of the usual

00:04:21.010 --> 00:04:25.340
photo-based wallpapers that you
get from other apps, it

00:04:25.340 --> 00:04:29.050
gives you access to more than
200,000 patterns created by

00:04:29.050 --> 00:04:31.720
the COLOURlovers community.

00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:34.780
And the cool thing about working
with patterns in the

00:04:34.780 --> 00:04:37.960
context of wallpapers is that
because they are tiled they

00:04:37.960 --> 00:04:40.830
will always look great on any
form factor, because they

00:04:40.830 --> 00:04:43.180
don't stretch or crop
or anything.

00:04:43.180 --> 00:04:46.860
So it always works great.

00:04:46.860 --> 00:04:48.730
That's the cool thing, and I
think that's one of the things

00:04:48.730 --> 00:04:51.750
that is attracting a lot of
attention to the app now.

00:04:51.750 --> 00:04:55.550
If I'm not mistaken, Pattrn was
one of the first apps to

00:04:55.550 --> 00:04:58.300
implement proper design
for Nexus 7.

00:04:58.300 --> 00:05:01.390
And I think maybe that was one
of the things that caught the

00:05:01.390 --> 00:05:04.690
attention of the Google folks.

00:05:04.690 --> 00:05:06.190
So that was an interesting
thing.

00:05:06.190 --> 00:05:10.050
And actually, I started working
on the Tablet UI

00:05:10.050 --> 00:05:11.970
because of the Nexus 7.

00:05:11.970 --> 00:05:12.750
It's a great device.

00:05:12.750 --> 00:05:13.240
I love it.

00:05:13.240 --> 00:05:14.640
I have one.

00:05:14.640 --> 00:05:18.870
And as part of the process, I
also implemented the 10 inch

00:05:18.870 --> 00:05:19.700
UI, of course.

00:05:19.700 --> 00:05:22.000
So it just made sense.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:27.160
So responsive design is probably
one of the most

00:05:27.160 --> 00:05:30.710
challenging things I had
to do on Pattrn.

00:05:30.710 --> 00:05:35.480
Although Pattrn is in kind of a
privileged position in terms

00:05:35.480 --> 00:05:40.680
of scalability just because the
content is so flexible in

00:05:40.680 --> 00:05:44.650
terms of stretching, like
filling areas, because we are

00:05:44.650 --> 00:05:45.970
tiling all the time.

00:05:45.970 --> 00:05:51.430
So you don't have a lot of the
constraints in terms of the

00:05:51.430 --> 00:05:52.450
content you're presenting.

00:05:52.450 --> 00:05:54.000
So that helped a lot.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:58.220
I had a lot of freedom to size
things properly without caring

00:05:58.220 --> 00:06:01.730
about looking bad in some form
factors for example.

00:06:01.730 --> 00:06:06.520
So there was one suggestion by
Roman Nurik which was to use

00:06:06.520 --> 00:06:08.940
grid on landscape on phones.

00:06:08.940 --> 00:06:10.620
And that's something I didn't
do just because I

00:06:10.620 --> 00:06:11.530
didn't have time to.

00:06:11.530 --> 00:06:14.410
But I definitely
want to do it.

00:06:14.410 --> 00:06:19.400
It's just one of those details
that make a lot of difference

00:06:19.400 --> 00:06:21.410
and I just didn't have
time to do it yet.

00:06:21.410 --> 00:06:26.680
But I do get a lot of
inspirations from other apps.

00:06:26.680 --> 00:06:29.880
This is one of the reasons
I watch the show.

00:06:29.880 --> 00:06:31.350
Not live, most of the time.

00:06:31.350 --> 00:06:35.620
But I always try to watch them
just because especially the

00:06:35.620 --> 00:06:40.570
design in action stuff.

00:06:40.570 --> 00:06:42.950
Especially that series
of proposed

00:06:42.950 --> 00:06:44.700
designs from the community.

00:06:44.700 --> 00:06:45.910
That was really inspiring.

00:06:45.910 --> 00:06:51.820
And I think the big message,
from that amount of designs--

00:06:51.820 --> 00:06:58.530
great designs that we got was
that there is clearly a design

00:06:58.530 --> 00:07:02.720
language arising in the Android
platform, and that

00:07:02.720 --> 00:07:08.290
helps, especially for developers
getting started in

00:07:08.290 --> 00:07:09.100
the platform.

00:07:09.100 --> 00:07:13.200
They have a reference, a visual
design to get started

00:07:13.200 --> 00:07:13.970
and that helps a lot.

00:07:13.970 --> 00:07:17.760
Especially if you don't have a
designer working with you.

00:07:17.760 --> 00:07:18.540
So that helps a lot.

00:07:18.540 --> 00:07:19.470
I'm not a designer.

00:07:19.470 --> 00:07:23.150
I tend to see myself as
a developer with a

00:07:23.150 --> 00:07:26.220
design eye to things.

00:07:26.220 --> 00:07:28.650
So having this design language
helps a lot.

00:07:28.650 --> 00:07:32.120
The think is, with any platform,
definitely just

00:07:32.120 --> 00:07:34.430
going through API Docs
doesn't help at all.

00:07:34.430 --> 00:07:39.740
So having some discussion, and
some reference designs, or

00:07:39.740 --> 00:07:42.630
even reference implementations
of certain aspects of the

00:07:42.630 --> 00:07:43.990
platform help a lot.

00:07:43.990 --> 00:07:48.990
So this is where I think the
design action shows help a

00:07:48.990 --> 00:07:54.010
lot, in terms of discussing one
topic and maybe talking

00:07:54.010 --> 00:07:56.510
about existing reference
implementations.

00:07:56.510 --> 00:07:59.020
And that helps a lot.

00:07:59.020 --> 00:08:01.870
Implementation wise, to be
honest, it wasn't that

00:08:01.870 --> 00:08:02.690
challenging.

00:08:02.690 --> 00:08:08.880
I think the big thing with
Pattrn was finding the right

00:08:08.880 --> 00:08:11.130
design for it.

00:08:11.130 --> 00:08:16.040
And I usually spend much more
time thinking about how things

00:08:16.040 --> 00:08:18.380
should look than implementing.

00:08:18.380 --> 00:08:22.100
One thing I did for Pattrn that
helped a lot was I did

00:08:22.100 --> 00:08:26.970
fragment-based implementation
from day one.

00:08:26.970 --> 00:08:29.630
So I didn't have to
reimplement the

00:08:29.630 --> 00:08:31.520
app to support tablets.

00:08:31.520 --> 00:08:36.970
So I started with a phony UI,
pretty much with one fragment

00:08:36.970 --> 00:08:37.939
inside one activity.

00:08:37.939 --> 00:08:42.270
So a one-to-one relationship
for every bit of the UI.

00:08:42.270 --> 00:08:47.110
So when I came to start working
on the tablet UI, it

00:08:47.110 --> 00:08:51.860
was a natural thing to just put
two pieces together in a

00:08:51.860 --> 00:08:52.480
different layout.

00:08:52.480 --> 00:08:53.420
So that helped a lot.

00:08:53.420 --> 00:08:56.230
I sketch a lot.

00:08:56.230 --> 00:08:59.480
I have a very thick notebook,
and I have several

00:08:59.480 --> 00:09:01.200
versions of the UI.

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:05.880
And I only start implementing
when I feel good about it.

00:09:05.880 --> 00:09:07.160
It doesn't need to be perfect.

00:09:07.160 --> 00:09:10.960
But I need to feel good about
the direction of things.

00:09:10.960 --> 00:09:15.300
And that helps in terms of
avoiding reimplementing stuff,

00:09:15.300 --> 00:09:18.350
just because you change your
mind while doing something.

00:09:18.350 --> 00:09:21.660
And of course, as any software
development, you'll

00:09:21.660 --> 00:09:22.600
learn as you do.

00:09:22.600 --> 00:09:24.670
There's nothing in software
development that is

00:09:24.670 --> 00:09:27.830
deterministic, like you know
what you're doing and you go

00:09:27.830 --> 00:09:29.430
until you end with
the same idea.

00:09:29.430 --> 00:09:31.280
So as you do it, you change

00:09:31.280 --> 00:09:33.160
direction, you tweak something.

00:09:33.160 --> 00:09:36.490
So actually there's something
interesting about

00:09:36.490 --> 00:09:37.650
the design of Pattrn.

00:09:37.650 --> 00:09:40.840
I started Pattrn, I wanted to
do something like a flick

00:09:40.840 --> 00:09:43.870
board thing of wallpapers.

00:09:43.870 --> 00:09:46.910
So it would look like
a magazine thing.

00:09:46.910 --> 00:09:51.600
And in the end, I just couldn't
find a way to make it

00:09:51.600 --> 00:09:53.780
look not right and nice.

00:09:53.780 --> 00:09:59.660
So that was about the time
the whole Holo thing

00:09:59.660 --> 00:10:01.700
started to pop up.

00:10:01.700 --> 00:10:08.610
So once I got the design
language of Holo, the ICS

00:10:08.610 --> 00:10:12.560
stuff, it just felt natural to
implement something that was

00:10:12.560 --> 00:10:13.990
more in line of Androids.

00:10:13.990 --> 00:10:15.890
Because flipboard is very--

00:10:15.890 --> 00:10:18.330
I mean, it's a nice design,
but it's alien.

00:10:18.330 --> 00:10:21.730
It's not really Android
in many ways.

00:10:21.730 --> 00:10:24.500
It has some bits of Android
there, but not really.

00:10:24.500 --> 00:10:27.960
So right now I'm working
on two things.

00:10:27.960 --> 00:10:32.000
One is editing features.

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:36.550
So allowing you to change colors
of existing patterns,

00:10:36.550 --> 00:10:39.770
adding brightness
and saturation,

00:10:39.770 --> 00:10:41.160
this kind of thing.

00:10:41.160 --> 00:10:42.410
A lot of people ask that.

00:10:42.410 --> 00:10:45.170
They like the pattern, but they
don't like the colors,

00:10:45.170 --> 00:10:46.250
this kind of thing.

00:10:46.250 --> 00:10:49.310
And the other thing is syncing
across devices.

00:10:49.310 --> 00:10:51.800
So you have favorites, your
wallpaper history.

00:10:51.800 --> 00:10:54.200
You want that across all your
different Android devices.

00:10:54.200 --> 00:10:55.500
And that's something
I'm working on now.

