Now there is a huge amount
of variation.

00:23:20.150 --> 00:23:22.960
We don't want every app to look
the same, some sort of

00:23:22.960 --> 00:23:24.070
cookie-cutter mold.

00:23:24.070 --> 00:23:25.290
That's kind of boring.

00:23:25.290 --> 00:23:27.620
But there are certain principles
which you can

00:23:27.620 --> 00:23:30.330
conform to which are going to
make sure that every Android

00:23:30.330 --> 00:23:32.680
user feels comfortable once
they get into the app.

00:23:32.680 --> 00:23:34.970
And this is something which the
Android Design in Action

00:23:34.970 --> 00:23:36.900
guys spend a lot of time
talking about on

00:23:36.900 --> 00:23:38.246
their Tuesday show.

00:23:38.246 --> 00:23:38.860
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah.

00:23:38.860 --> 00:23:42.810
This is when the way we got
these is by hiring an

00:23:42.810 --> 00:23:46.360
excellent design team and
letting them run loose for a

00:23:46.360 --> 00:23:49.340
while until they figured out
exactly what the design

00:23:49.340 --> 00:23:51.600
language of Ice Cream Sandwich
was going to be.

00:23:51.600 --> 00:23:55.020
And even though we expect that
to evolve, we don't expect

00:23:55.020 --> 00:23:58.730
that to ever completely change
the way it did in Ice Cream

00:23:58.730 --> 00:23:59.510
Sandwich again.

00:23:59.510 --> 00:24:03.240
This is, for the foreseeable
future, what Android apps

00:24:03.240 --> 00:24:06.760
should look like unless you have
a really good reason to

00:24:06.760 --> 00:24:08.130
not make them look that way.

00:24:08.130 --> 00:24:10.300
RETO MEIER: So once you've
sort of gone through and

00:24:10.300 --> 00:24:14.480
created all of these basic
requirements for building an

00:24:14.480 --> 00:24:16.430
app, which we're going to be
really excited about and are

00:24:16.430 --> 00:24:18.740
going to be willing to feature
on our own collection--

00:24:18.740 --> 00:24:21.450
in a collection we're going
to put our names against.

00:24:21.450 --> 00:24:22.445
There's a few--

00:24:22.445 --> 00:24:23.810
IAN NI-LEWIS: Actually, I think
just your name's on it.

00:24:23.810 --> 00:24:25.000
RETO MEIER: Right now
it's just my name.

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:27.010
I don't think you're quite
that comfortable yet.

00:24:27.010 --> 00:24:28.250
But nonetheless.

00:24:28.250 --> 00:24:31.460
The next thing we're looking for
is something which makes

00:24:31.460 --> 00:24:35.600
an even Pure-r-er Android than
just those basic criteria.

00:24:35.600 --> 00:24:37.730
And these are things which
are kind of ephemeral.

00:24:37.730 --> 00:24:40.860
This isn't stuff that you can
easily define in a checklist.

00:24:40.860 --> 00:24:43.330
We want something that's really
efficient, that's

00:24:43.330 --> 00:24:45.850
buttery smooth, it gives you
this sort of magical

00:24:45.850 --> 00:24:47.870
experience when you're
using the app.

00:24:47.870 --> 00:24:50.210
You kind of launch and you're
like, oh this is kind of cool.

00:24:50.210 --> 00:24:51.450
IAN NI-LEWIS: It just
totally works.

00:24:51.450 --> 00:24:52.860
Yeah, it feels right.

00:24:52.860 --> 00:24:53.360
Exactly.

00:24:53.360 --> 00:24:56.830
And efficient, I think we're
talking about, how easy is it

00:24:56.830 --> 00:24:59.480
to get tasks done in the app?

00:24:59.480 --> 00:25:02.160
Buttery, on the other hand, I
think we're really referring

00:25:02.160 --> 00:25:04.940
to the efficiency
of your code.

00:25:04.940 --> 00:25:08.340
And that one actually,
personally, I can measure.

00:25:08.340 --> 00:25:12.120
If your code is running
consistently at 30 to 60 FPS

00:25:12.120 --> 00:25:14.750
on a newer device, then
it's not buttery.

00:25:14.750 --> 00:25:15.590
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:25:15.590 --> 00:25:17.560
And we're also looking at
efficiency and butteriness in

00:25:17.560 --> 00:25:19.910
terms of things like
your battery life.

00:25:19.910 --> 00:25:22.070
You don't want to have the user
being conscious of the

00:25:22.070 --> 00:25:24.480
fact that your app is doing
anything other than running

00:25:24.480 --> 00:25:26.770
without draining your
battery at all.

00:25:26.770 --> 00:25:30.720
I think a good example of that
delightful aspect is something

00:25:30.720 --> 00:25:34.150
like Pattrn, which creates
attractive wallpapers or

00:25:34.150 --> 00:25:35.790
allows you to browse attractive
wallpapers.

00:25:35.790 --> 00:25:39.330
Now, I don't really change the
wallpapers on my app, but I

00:25:39.330 --> 00:25:41.330
found myself when looking at
this app, just sort of

00:25:41.330 --> 00:25:44.310
flicking through and just having
fun with something

00:25:44.310 --> 00:25:47.100
which isn't necessarily
something I normally would.

00:25:47.100 --> 00:25:49.790
IAN NI-LEWIS: Whereas Tasks
delighted me, even though it

00:25:49.790 --> 00:25:53.880
is the simplest app possible,
they just didn't

00:25:53.880 --> 00:25:55.490
get anything wrong.

00:25:55.490 --> 00:25:57.280
All I wanted was a task list.

00:25:57.280 --> 00:26:00.130
I didn't need a skeuomorphic
design, I didn't need bells

00:26:00.130 --> 00:26:02.950
and whistles, I just needed
the task list that worked

00:26:02.950 --> 00:26:05.360
exactly the way I expected
it to work.

00:26:05.360 --> 00:26:07.810
And everything that they added,
whether it's the list

00:26:07.810 --> 00:26:11.480
drag and drop or whatever, was
something that added to my

00:26:11.480 --> 00:26:14.660
sense of the app responding
the way I expected it to.

00:26:14.660 --> 00:26:16.290
RETO MEIER: Absolutely.

00:26:16.290 --> 00:26:19.770
So I think that pretty much
wraps it up for us today.

